👉 Logical Operators in JAVA : 

Logical operators are used to combine conditions or change the result of a condition.
They are mostly used with if statements.

The three most common logical operators in Java are:

&& (AND)
|| (OR)
! (NOT)

1. && (Logical AND)

It returns true only if both conditions are true.
If even one condition is false, the result is false.

Example : 

int age = 20;
boolean hasID = true;

if (age >= 18 && hasID) {
    System.out.println("You can enter.");
}

Output: 

You can enter.
Because both conditions are true.

2. || (Logical OR)

It returns true if at least one condition is true.
It becomes false only when both conditions are false.

Example : 

boolean isSunday = false;
boolean isHoliday = true;

if (isSunday || isHoliday) {
    System.out.println("You can relax today!");
}

Output: 

You can relax today!
Because one condition is true.

3. ! (Logical NOT)

It reverses the result.
If the condition is true → it becomes false
If the condition is false → it becomes true

Example :

boolean isRaining = false;

if (!isRaining) {
    System.out.println("You can go outside.");
}

Output:

You can go outside.
Because !false becomes true.

👉 Simple Summary

&& → Both must be true
|| → At least one must be true
! → Reverses the condition

These operators help us make better decisions in Java programs.
